258
00:11:01,511 --> 00:11:03,012
Moishe's gonna explode.

259
00:11:03,096 --> 00:11:04,805
-Who the fuck is Moishe?
-My father-in-law.

260
00:11:04,889 --> 00:11:06,307
He's gonna see that, and he's gonna know

261
00:11:06,391 --> 00:11:07,725
-that I was fired.
-So what?

262
00:11:07,809 --> 00:11:09,935
He loaned me the money to
buy back my old apartment,

263
00:11:10,019 --> 00:11:11,729
my collateral being my contract

264
00:11:11,813 --> 00:11:13,439
for the tour and the Christmas special.

265
00:11:13,523 --> 00:11:15,941
He was so excited about
the Christmas special.

266
00:11:16,025 --> 00:11:19,111
You bought back your old apartment?

267
00:11:19,195 --> 00:11:20,988
-Yes.
-When?

268
00:11:21,072 --> 00:11:23,490
-Yesterday.
-I was with you yesterday.

269
00:11:23,574 --> 00:11:25,326
-Not all day.
-I can't believe this.

270
00:11:25,410 --> 00:11:26,785
I leave you alone for four hours,

271
00:11:26,869 --> 00:11:28,620
and you blow your career
and buy an apartment.

272
00:11:28,704 --> 00:11:30,247
You said I didn't blow my career.

273
00:11:30,331 --> 00:11:32,791
Why would you buy an apartment?
You don't have any money!

274
00:11:32,875 --> 00:11:35,210
What do you mean, I don't have any money?

275
00:11:35,294 --> 00:11:37,254
You have some money, clearly.

276
00:11:37,338 --> 00:11:39,607
I saved every cent from
the first part of the tour.

277
00:11:39,691 --> 00:11:40,008
I know.

278
00:11:40,092 --> 00:11:42,552
And I am holding it for you. I just…

279
00:11:43,845 --> 00:11:45,429
Why would you buy back your apartment?

280
00:11:45,513 --> 00:11:47,014
Because I don't want to live

281
00:11:47,098 --> 00:11:50,100
with my ex-in-laws in Queens anymore.

282
00:11:50,184 --> 00:11:51,769
Look, I know it was
an emotional purchase,

283
00:11:51,853 --> 00:11:53,228
but I did it, it's done.

284
00:11:53,312 --> 00:11:54,897
And now I need to get something

285
00:11:54,981 --> 00:11:57,817
into his hands immediately,
buy me some time.

286
00:12:00,111 --> 00:12:01,696
So I need my money.

287
00:12:02,738 --> 00:12:03,822
When?

288
00:12:03,906 --> 00:12:06,033
Today.

289
00:12:06,117 --> 00:12:07,952
Okay. Sure.

290
00:12:08,995 --> 00:12:11,497
I'll get you your money today.

291
00:12:11,581 --> 00:12:14,291
I don't have my ledger book on me.

292
00:12:14,375 --> 00:12:16,502
I just got to look at
the ledger at least,

293
00:12:16,586 --> 00:12:18,128
make sure things are ledgered.

294
00:12:18,212 --> 00:12:19,630
Fine.

295
00:12:19,714 --> 00:12:23,425
And there were some expenses
I had to deduct from your money.

296
00:12:23,509 --> 00:12:26,136
-Business expenses, all legit.
-Okay.

297
00:12:26,220 --> 00:12:27,805
And I bought some hairspray.
Remember the hairspray?

298
00:12:27,889 --> 00:12:29,223
You asked me to buy some hairspray.

299
00:12:29,307 --> 00:12:30,891
-Absolutely.
-Okay.

300
00:12:30,975 --> 00:12:32,935
I'll look at the ledger, get to the bank.

301
00:12:33,019 --> 00:12:34,311
You'll get your money,

302
00:12:34,395 --> 00:12:36,105
sans the really expensive hairspray.

303
00:12:36,189 --> 00:12:38,107
Great. Thank you.

304
00:12:38,191 --> 00:12:40,192
I don't know what you
need all that hairspray for,

305
00:12:40,276 --> 00:12:42,528
but that's your business, so…

306
00:12:44,447 --> 00:12:46,281
-Were you gonna make a call?
-What?

307
00:12:46,365 --> 00:12:48,158
I can go in the back if
you need some privacy.

308
00:12:48,242 --> 00:12:49,701
No, I was not gonna make a call.

309
00:12:49,785 --> 00:12:51,328
Just 'cause you stand next to a phone,

310
00:12:51,412 --> 00:12:53,414
people think you're gonna make a call.

311
00:12:53,498 --> 00:12:54,873
You know what?

312
00:12:54,957 --> 00:12:56,875
I'm gonna get some fresh air.

313
00:12:56,959 --> 00:12:59,086
Stretch the legs.

314
00:12:59,170 --> 00:13:01,422
-You want anything?
-Just my money.

315
00:13:01,506 --> 00:13:02,756
Yep.

316
00:13:02,840 --> 00:13:04,634
I'll be right back.

317
00:13:09,180 --> 00:13:11,830
[JIMMIE LUNCEFORD:
"RHYTHM IS OUR BUSINESS"]

318
00:13:26,072 --> 00:13:27,823
Hey. I got to use the phone.

319
00:13:27,907 --> 00:13:29,867
I'm currently wooing a lady.

320
00:13:29,951 --> 00:13:32,578
-Okay.
-I… You hung up.

321
00:13:32,662 --> 00:13:34,163
If you tied the ropes tight enough,

322
00:13:34,247 --> 00:13:36,247
she'll still be there when you get back.

323
00:13:39,085 --> 00:13:41,087
[PHONE RINGING]

324
00:13:42,421 --> 00:13:44,173
-Huh?
-SUSIE: <i>Tess, it's me.</i>

325
00:13:44,257 --> 00:13:45,799
Susie? It's so early.

326
00:13:45,883 --> 00:13:47,593
Have we heard from that guy
from the insurance company?

327
00:13:47,677 --> 00:13:49,136
<i>-I really got to get…</i>
-Wait.

328
00:13:49,220 --> 00:13:50,762
<i>What?</i>

329
00:13:50,846 --> 00:13:52,389
-[SKINT SNORTS]
-[SIGHS]

330
00:13:52,473 --> 00:13:54,766
-Shit.
<i>-What?</i>

331
00:13:54,850 --> 00:13:57,269
Ah, for a moment, I
thought Skint was dead.

332
00:13:57,353 --> 00:13:58,687
<i>Well, that's my life in a nutshell.</i>

333
00:13:58,771 --> 00:13:59,897
Fucking focus here.

334
00:13:59,981 --> 00:14:01,523
-Check. I need the check.
<i>-Yes.</i>

335
00:14:01,607 --> 00:14:03,192
He called yesterday,
said we could come by

336
00:14:03,276 --> 00:14:04,651
and pick it up at the office.

337
00:14:04,735 --> 00:14:06,737
Great. Good. We are going this morning.

338
00:14:06,821 --> 00:14:08,197
I will be by in an hour.

339
00:14:08,281 --> 00:14:10,199
<i>-All right. Geez.</i>
-[SIGHS]

340
00:14:14,537 --> 00:14:17,957
JOEL: Hi. Uh… Can I help you?

341
00:14:19,041 --> 00:14:23,129
Why? Are you with the… Wait. Hold on.

342
00:14:24,589 --> 00:14:26,048
Ha.

343
00:14:26,132 --> 00:14:27,966
I'm actually getting pretty fluent here.

344
00:14:28,050 --> 00:14:30,636
I ordered tea, and I told
the plumber to fix the toilet.

345
00:14:30,720 --> 00:14:32,346
I got tea, and he fixed the sink,

346
00:14:32,430 --> 00:14:34,640
so we're getting close.

347
00:14:34,724 --> 00:14:36,183
Here we go.

348
00:14:36,267 --> 00:14:37,852
<i>Ni hao.</i>

349
00:14:38,936 --> 00:14:41,314
There's more. Just, um…

350
00:14:42,857 --> 00:14:44,692
<i>You méi you…</i>

351
00:14:45,901 --> 00:14:48,779
Something, something.
Where the hell is "something"?

352
00:14:48,863 --> 00:14:50,906
Wait. I'll find it.

353
00:14:51,949 --> 00:14:57,162
Uh… <i>You méi you nali women keyi…</i>

354
00:14:57,246 --> 00:14:59,164
Uh, hold on.

355
00:14:59,248 --> 00:15:00,958
Five minutes.

356
00:15:01,042 --> 00:15:05,713
<i>You bing gang gen…</i> Yep. Right behind you.

357
00:15:08,257 --> 00:15:10,676
[MAN, WOMAN CONVERSING IN MANDARIN]

358
00:15:21,854 --> 00:15:24,356
How do you know what I want you to do?

359
00:15:24,440 --> 00:15:26,817
You don't listen.
You just care about you.

360
00:15:26,901 --> 00:15:28,569
What you want.

361
00:15:28,653 --> 00:15:29,987
That is not true.

362
00:15:30,071 --> 00:15:31,321
I work very hard for this family!

363
00:15:31,405 --> 00:15:33,824
I am always the one you send in to…

364
00:15:34,450 --> 00:15:35,451
You rang?

365
00:15:36,410 --> 00:15:38,787
Really? You sent Li Wei after him?

366
00:15:38,871 --> 00:15:39,861
You want to tell me what's going on?

367
00:15:39,945 --> 00:15:41,164
[IN ENGLISH] I didn't
know they were gonna

368
00:15:41,248 --> 00:15:43,000
send him up there…
or that he could fit through the door.

369
00:15:43,084 --> 00:15:45,086
[MAN SPEAKING MANDARIN]

370
00:15:48,464 --> 00:15:50,465
He says he hears your club is doing well.

371
00:15:50,549 --> 00:15:52,884
-Hold on.
-You're kidding, right?

372
00:15:52,968 --> 00:15:54,219
This is my neighborhood now.

373
00:15:54,303 --> 00:15:56,013
I'm gonna learn to speak the language.

374
00:15:56,097 --> 00:15:57,514
-Uh, okay.
-[FLIPPING PAGES]

375
00:15:57,598 --> 00:15:59,766
Uh, my… place… of…

376
00:15:59,850 --> 00:16:02,227
Joel, people have a life expectancy.

377
00:16:02,311 --> 00:16:05,314
Yep.
Tell them the club is doing sensational.

378
00:16:05,398 --> 00:16:08,108
Great buzz.
First few nights completely sold out.

379
00:16:08,192 --> 00:16:11,069
[SPEAKING MANDARIN]

380
00:16:11,153 --> 00:16:13,405
And I have big plans for the place.

381
00:16:13,489 --> 00:16:15,198
Uh, private events, specialty nights.

382
00:16:15,282 --> 00:16:16,700
I'm thinking of putting in a kitchen

383
00:16:16,784 --> 00:16:18,160
and starting food service.

384
00:16:18,244 --> 00:16:21,038
[SPEAKING MANDARIN]

385
00:16:21,122 --> 00:16:22,456
JOEL: Hey, can you amp up

386
00:16:22,540 --> 00:16:24,625
the excitement a little?
I'm selling here.

387
00:16:24,709 --> 00:16:29,921
No! No food.
No private events. No kitchen.

388
00:16:30,005 --> 00:16:31,465
Food will make the money smell.

389
00:16:31,549 --> 00:16:35,344
He either stops doing
well or he just stops.

390
00:16:35,428 --> 00:16:36,928
-What did he say?
-MEI: I can't tell him that.

391
00:16:37,012 --> 00:16:37,929
What did you say?

392
00:16:38,013 --> 00:16:39,473
You tell him now.

393
00:16:39,557 --> 00:16:40,807
Mei, please.
What are your parents upset about?

394
00:16:40,891 --> 00:16:42,351
I never said they were my parents.

395
00:16:42,435 --> 00:16:44,019
She used to listen to you.

396
00:16:44,103 --> 00:16:45,729
You let her go to school.

397
00:16:45,813 --> 00:16:46,938
It's a law!

398
00:16:47,022 --> 00:16:49,608
I've got parents.
That sounds like parents to me.

399
00:16:49,692 --> 00:16:51,318
You've grown too close to this man.

400
00:16:51,402 --> 00:16:52,819
This is not why we brought you into this.

401
00:16:52,903 --> 00:16:54,196
I did everything I could!

402
00:16:54,280 --> 00:16:55,781
I gave him a jukebox with
nothing but Chinese records

403
00:16:55,865 --> 00:16:57,407
in it, for Christ's sake!

404
00:16:57,491 --> 00:17:01,870
That was months ago.
Now I hear you bring him toilet paper.

405
00:17:01,954 --> 00:17:03,455
No more!

406
00:17:03,539 --> 00:17:06,333
You will have no more
contact with that man.

407
00:17:06,417 --> 00:17:07,959
You tell him to leave.

408
00:17:08,043 --> 00:17:09,628
Now!

409
00:17:10,796 --> 00:17:12,839
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

410
00:17:12,923 --> 00:17:16,385
-So…
-The club is doing too well.

411
00:17:16,469 --> 00:17:18,387
Most landlords want
their tenants to do well.

412
00:17:18,471 --> 00:17:19,888
I never said they were the landlords.

413
00:17:19,972 --> 00:17:22,349
-Mei…
-They wanted a business that looked legit

414
00:17:22,433 --> 00:17:24,101
but didn't cause too much of a splash.

415
00:17:24,185 --> 00:17:26,728
A dud club means less eyes on the parlor.

416
00:17:26,812 --> 00:17:29,189
A successful club means eyes.

417
00:17:29,273 --> 00:17:31,900
They just assumed your club would fail.

418
00:17:31,984 --> 00:17:33,235
Why?

419
00:17:33,319 --> 00:17:35,112
'Cause you're a Jewish
ex-plastics salesman

420
00:17:35,196 --> 00:17:36,613
who suddenly opened a club in Chinatown

421
00:17:36,697 --> 00:17:39,074
with an English to Chinese
dictionary from the 1800s.

422
00:17:39,158 --> 00:17:43,120
-I… shit.
-My expectations were low.

423
00:17:43,204 --> 00:17:44,871
Well, why are they mad at you?

424
00:17:44,955 --> 00:17:47,833
Because I was supposed
to make sure you failed.

425
00:17:47,917 --> 00:17:49,626
Is that why you gave me a jukebox

426
00:17:49,710 --> 00:17:51,044
with nothing but Chinese records in it?

427
00:17:51,128 --> 00:17:52,963
No. That was a gift. Please.

428
00:17:53,047 --> 00:17:55,549
JOEL: So, if I'm reading the room right,

429
00:17:55,633 --> 00:17:57,592
the people who may or
may not be your parents

430
00:17:57,676 --> 00:17:59,678
and may or may not be my landlords,

431
00:17:59,762 --> 00:18:01,972
-they either want me to fail or…
-Leave.

432
00:18:02,056 --> 00:18:05,476
I thought "or die," so "leave" is better.

433
00:18:07,061 --> 00:18:10,814
Hey, Mata Hari, what side are you on now?

434
00:18:10,898 --> 00:18:13,483
Your side. I swear.

435
00:18:13,567 --> 00:18:15,986
I'm not sure if that helps me or not.

436
00:18:19,532 --> 00:18:20,866
Thank you.

437
00:18:21,116 --> 00:18:22,535
You're welcome, man.

438
00:18:27,122 --> 00:18:29,472
[ROSEMARY CLOONEY:
"FUZZY WUZZY (WUZ A BEAR)"]

439
00:18:32,670 --> 00:18:34,129
-[KIDS CHATTERING]
-Faster! Faster! Faster!

440
00:18:34,213 --> 00:18:37,549
-Look, look!
-Oh, Ethan, that's wonderful.

441
00:18:37,633 --> 00:18:40,594
You know, when I was a boy, I had a sock.

442
00:18:40,678 --> 00:18:42,095
That was my toy.

443
00:18:42,179 --> 00:18:44,931
Stuck my hand in it and said,
"Where did my fingers go?"

444
00:18:45,015 --> 00:18:47,350
That was the game. The end.

445
00:18:47,434 --> 00:18:49,352
And nobody cares.

446
00:18:49,436 --> 00:18:50,771
Well said, Moishe.

447
00:18:50,855 --> 00:18:53,690
I have knishes hot out of the oven.

448
00:18:53,774 --> 00:18:56,234
-What are you reading?
-A book.

449
00:18:56,318 --> 00:18:59,112
-Is it <i>Peter Rabbit?</i>
-It is not <i>Peter Rabbit.</i>

450
00:18:59,196 --> 00:19:01,198
I read <i>Peter Rabbit.</i>

451
00:19:01,282 --> 00:19:02,824
Next up, Proust.

452
00:19:02,908 --> 00:19:05,076
Why do you have fur on your lip?

453
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:07,287
That's called a mustache.

454
00:19:07,371 --> 00:19:09,831
[CHUCKLES] It looks
like a crawly caterpillar.

455
00:19:09,915 --> 00:19:11,708
-[LAUGHS]
-It does not.

456
00:19:11,792 --> 00:19:13,543
-It does.
-I think it moved.

457
00:19:13,627 --> 00:19:15,170
-That's because I'm talking.
-[LAUGHING]

458
00:19:15,254 --> 00:19:16,838
-[PHONE RINGING]
-Stop that.

459
00:19:16,922 --> 00:19:18,757
-I'll get it.
-No, I'll get it.

460
00:19:18,841 --> 00:19:21,218
-ROSE: I'm already up.
-But I'm getting it! Rose.

461
00:19:21,302 --> 00:19:23,386
-Abe, my goodness.
-Well, they're being mean.

462
00:19:23,470 --> 00:19:26,264
None of the grown-ups
are doing anything to stop it.

463
00:19:26,348 --> 00:19:28,558
-Shit.
-Hello? Maisel residence.

464
00:19:28,642 --> 00:19:30,018
MIDGE: <i>Shirley? It's Miriam.</i>

465
00:19:30,102 --> 00:19:33,104
Miriam, hello. It's Miriam.

466
00:19:33,188 --> 00:19:34,940
Where are you calling from? Prague?

467
00:19:35,024 --> 00:19:37,734
-Yes. I'm in Prague.
-Well, take a lot of pictures,

468
00:19:37,818 --> 00:19:39,402
and tell them you love Jesus Christ.

469
00:19:39,486 --> 00:19:41,696
It sounds pretty lively over there.
What's going on?

470
00:19:41,780 --> 00:19:43,824
<i>-It's Ethan's birthday.</i>
-No, it's not.

471
00:19:43,908 --> 00:19:45,659
Yes, it is. I made three cakes.

472
00:19:45,743 --> 00:19:47,327
<i>Shirley, it's not Ethan's birthday.</i>

473
00:19:47,411 --> 00:19:49,996
Whatever you say.
I have to check the cutlets.

474
00:19:50,080 --> 00:19:52,082
Speak to your father.

475
00:19:54,251 --> 00:19:56,044
Hello, Miriam? Are you in Prague?

476
00:19:56,128 --> 00:19:58,630
Make sure you work Jesus
Christ into every conversation.

477
00:19:58,714 --> 00:20:01,174
I will. Hey, why did Shirley say
Ethan's having a birthday party?

478
00:20:01,258 --> 00:20:03,134
-His birthday's in November.
<i>-Not anymore.</i>

479
00:20:03,218 --> 00:20:04,803
What… What do you mean, "not anymore"?

480
00:20:04,887 --> 00:20:07,138
Eh, November was bad for us.
I have deadlines.

481
00:20:07,222 --> 00:20:09,307
Moishe has his spring fabrics arriving.

482
00:20:09,391 --> 00:20:11,893
Shirley's cousin Yetta
is coming for a visit.

483
00:20:11,977 --> 00:20:13,436
I don't know what your mother's doing,

484
00:20:13,520 --> 00:20:16,231
-but it was bad for her, too.
-ROSE: I have work, Abe.

485
00:20:16,315 --> 00:20:18,692
Your mother claims she has work,

486
00:20:18,776 --> 00:20:20,193
<i>so it just didn't work for any of us.</i>

487
00:20:20,277 --> 00:20:23,321
Are you seriously telling me
you rescheduled Ethan's birthday?

488
00:20:23,405 --> 00:20:24,489
<i>He's five.</i>

489
00:20:24,573 --> 00:20:26,032
-What does he know?
<i>-Papa!</i>

490
00:20:26,116 --> 00:20:28,827
What? The boy has three cakes,

491
00:20:28,911 --> 00:20:30,453
and we're taking him to Coney Island

492
00:20:30,537 --> 00:20:32,706
-to ride the Wonder Wheel.
-I can't believe this.

493
00:20:32,790 --> 00:20:35,208
How does this affect you?
You weren't going to be here

494
00:20:35,292 --> 00:20:37,043
-for it anyhow.
-What's the matter?

495
00:20:37,127 --> 00:20:39,087
ABE: <i>Miriam's upset we
changed Ethan's birthday.</i>

496
00:20:39,171 --> 00:20:40,505
-ROSE: <i>Why?</i>
-ABE: <i>No idea.</i>

497
00:20:40,589 --> 00:20:43,341
Papa, you don't just
change a little boy's birthday.

498
00:20:43,425 --> 00:20:44,843
We changed your brother's birthday twice.

499
00:20:44,927 --> 00:20:46,511
-He never found out.
<i>-You…</i>

500
00:20:46,595 --> 00:20:48,346
Who are you people?

501
00:20:48,430 --> 00:20:51,057
<i>This borders on inhuman and unfeeling</i>

502
00:20:51,141 --> 00:20:53,143
and… Wait, did you change <i>my</i> birthday?

503
00:20:53,227 --> 00:20:55,061
No. Listen, Miriam,

